 1339–":"oko 1339.–preminula","1335–Male":"1335–preminuo","1360–1440":"1360.–1440","1339–Female":"1339–preminula","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"oko 1339.","1440":"1440","1360":"1360.","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England"},"cs":{"about 1339–":"okolo 1339–Zesnulá","1335–Male":"1335–Zesnulý","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Zesnulá","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"okolo 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1339–":"omkring 1339–Afdød","1335–Male":"1335–Afdød","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Afdød","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"omkring 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1339–":"circa 1339–Overleden","1335–Male":"1335–Overleden","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Overleden","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"circa 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1339–":"about 1339–Deceased","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Deceased","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"about 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Babcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): although the first element of this name would suggest it is derived from the Middle English personal name <i>Babb</i> (see   Babb  ), apparently it is a post-medieval form of <b>Badcock</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Badecok</i>, a pet form of <i>Bade</i> (see   Bade  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-cok</i>. There is no reason why a Middle English <i>Babbecok</i>, a pet form of <i>Babb</i> (itself a pet form of   Barbara  ), should not have existed, but evidence has yet to be found.","History: James Babcock settled in Portsmouth, RI, in 1642."],"variants":[{"name":"Babb","meanings":["English (Devon, Somerset, and Cornwall): from the Middle English personal name <i>Babb(e)</i>, usually no doubt a pet form of the female personal name <i>Barbara</i> (see   Barbara  ), but possibly in some cases a survival of the Old English personal name <i>Babba</i>, which is found in several placenames, including Babbacombe in Devon and Babington in Somerset.","English (Devon, Somerset, and Cornwall): from Middle English <i>babe</i> ‘infant, young child’, applied as a nickname.","Americanized form of German   Bobb   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":43,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":116,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sir Robert Babcock was born about 1339, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert Babcock."},"et":{"about 1339–":"umbes 1339–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Surnud","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1339–":"noin 1339–Kuollut","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Kuollut","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"noin 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1339–":"environ 1339–Décédée","1335–Male":"1335–Décédé","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Décédée","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"environ 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sir Robert Babcock est née environ 1339, à Oxford, Oxfordshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Robert Babcock."},"de":{"about 1339–":"um 1339–Verstorben","1335–Male":"1335–Verstorben","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Verstorben","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"um 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford, Oxfordshire, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sir Robert Babcock wurde um 1339 in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England geboren. Sie hatte mit Robert Babcock mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"about 1339–":"about 1339–Desede","1335–Male":"1335–Desede","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1339–Female":"1339–Desede","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","about 1339":"about 1339","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Oxford, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxford,